### Interfaces in Java

An interface is a reference type that contains abstract methods (until Java 7). It defines a contract that implementing classes must fulfill.

---

### Interface Declaration

```java
interface Animal {
    void makeSound();  // implicitly public and abstract
    void eat();
}
```

---

### Implementing Interfaces

```java
class Dog implements Animal {
    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }

    @Override
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Dog eats");
    }
}
```

---

### Interface Features (Java 8+)

| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Default methods | `default` keyword, provide default implementation |
| Static methods | `static` methods with body |
| Private methods (Java 9+) | Helper methods within interface |

---

### Multiple Inheritance via Interfaces

A class can implement multiple interfaces:

```java
interface Flyable {
    void fly();
}

interface Swimmable {
    void swim();
}

class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable {
    public void fly() { System.out.println("Flying"); }
    public void swim() { System.out.println("Swimming"); }
}
```

---

### Interface vs Abstract Class

| Feature | Interface | Abstract Class |
|---------|-----------|---------------|
| Multiple inheritance | Yes | No |
| Fields | public static final only | Any fields |
| Constructors | No | Yes |
| Methods (pre-Java 8) | Abstract only | Any methods |

> **Key Point:** Interfaces enable multiple inheritance of behavior. All interface methods are implicitly `public`. From Java 8, interfaces can have `default` and `static` methods with bodies.

codeExample:
interface Drawable {
    void draw();
    default void print() {
        System.out.println("Printing...");
    }
}

interface Resizable {
    void resize(double factor);
}

class Circle implements Drawable, Resizable {
    private double radius;

    Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing circle with radius " + radius);
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(double factor) {
        radius *= factor;
        System.out.println("Resized to radius " + radius);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Circle c = new Circle(5);
        c.draw();
        c.resize(2.0);
        c.print();  // default method
    }
}
